Traditional rulers in the nine states of the Niger Delta region have faulted the adoption of open and cash disbursement to vulnerable Nigerians to cushion the effect of COVID-19 which has caused economic and social hardships on Nigerians. The monarchs under the aegis of the Rural Chiefs’ Peace and Development Initiatives, said that though the intention by the federal government was laudable, the open and hand disbursement of cash is intended to perpetuate fraud, rubbish the cashless policy of the present administration and promote selective payments. In a statement issued yesterday in Yenagoa, Bayelsa State by the group’s national chairman, Chief Nengi James-Eriworio, he stated that the decision to adopt open display of cash and payment was shameful and questioned the integrity of the President Muhammdu Buhari administration in the area of accountability, probity and good governance. The chiefs said that their preliminary investigations had shown that while the federal government through the Nigeria Centre for Disease Control (NCDC) could reach Nigerians through text messages on issues of sensitisation on the COVID-19 pandemic,” they have decided to jettison the Bank Verification Number (BVN) system and other means of online payments that will reach over 90 per cent of vulnerable persons in the country and safeguard fraud.” They also faulted the composition of the committee handling the disbursement of the N20,000 palliative to the vulnerable, insisting that the members of the the Economic and Financial Crime Commission (EFCC), the ICPC, the Civil Society groups, members of the National Assembly and the traditional rulers should have been included to ensure transparency and accountability “We urge President Muhammdu Buhari not to accept a fake report of proper disbursement from the committee without getting a firsthand confirmation that vulnerable Nigerians have received the monies .It is clear that there is element of fraud ongoing within the committee,”. “In the Niger Delta, we are yet to see the disbursement of the N20,000 palliative by the federal government. If they are to distribute the money, would they carry the cash to coastal communities to disburse? The federal government is playing with the emotions of the people of the region,” he said. 